body:
Hi,

Let's say I want to use Verilator not for any real RTL simulation, but just to dump out the AST from some Verilog designs. If I have a code segment like so:

```
reg clk;
always @(*) begin
  clk = 1'b0;
  #1;
  clk = 1'b1;
  #1;
end
```

When I run this through `verilator myfile.v --xml-only`, I can see that Verilator understands the separate assignments of `clk = 1'b0` and `clk = 1'b1`, but not the delay statements. I'm not sure if this is "by design" (since Verilator doesn't support arbitrary unit-delays), or if there is some kind of extra flag that can at least include this syntax in the AST (even if it's effectively a no-op from the code generation's perspective).
